## Notes

### Immutable attributes (force destroy + recreate)

The Cleura edit API cannot change the following after creation. Changing any of them in your configuration forces Terraform to **destroy and recreate the entire cluster** â€” every worker node, workload, and its data is lost, and the API endpoint changes. Terraform emits a plan-time warning for each. Make sure the downtime is acceptable before applying.

- **`name`** â€” the cluster name is fixed. It is also the resource's identity (see [Import](#import)) and must be 1â€“15 characters of letters, digits, or hyphens.
- **`networking.type`** â€” the CNI plugin (`calico` or `cilium`) is set only at creation. Switching between them (in either direction) recreates the cluster.
- **`enable_ha_control_plane`, only when going `true` â†’ `false`.** Enabling control-plane high availability (`false` â†’ `true`) is applied in place, but **disabling** it once enabled cannot be done in place and forces a recreate. (Re-sending an unchanged `true` is intentionally suppressed to avoid an API 409.)
- **`shoot_provider.load_balancer_provider`** â€” fixed at creation.
- **`shoot_provider.infrastructure_config` fields** â€” `floating_pool_name` is always immutable. `network_id`, `router_id`, and `workers_network_cidr` are `Optional + Computed`: if you omit them, Cleura creates and manages the network/router/CIDR and Terraform pins the assigned values (so omitting them never causes a perpetual replace). If you instead set one explicitly to attach to an existing network, later changing that explicit value forces a recreate.

Worker groups, by contrast, are reconciled **in place**: they are matched by their (immutable) `name`, so groups added, removed, or edited in `shoot_provider.workers` are created, deleted, or updated on the running cluster without recreating it. Keep each worker group's `name` stable â€” renaming a group reads as deleting the old one and adding a new one. Adding or removing groups emits a warning about possible temporary downtime or over-provisioning.

### Calico vs. Cilium

`networking.type` accepts `calico` or `cilium`. The `networking.cilium_provider_config` block (Hubble, encryption, tunnel mode, etc.) **applies only to Cilium**. Setting `cilium_provider_config` while `type` is anything other than `"cilium"` (including Calico) is rejected at plan time â€” remove the block or set `type = "cilium"`. Because `type` is immutable, choose the CNI up front: moving an existing Calico cluster to Cilium (or vice-versa) requires a recreate.

On create, `networking.type` and `cilium_provider_config` are both settable. On update, only `cilium_provider_config` can change in place; `type` is immutable as described above. Within `cilium_provider_config`, `tunnel` is one of `vxlan`, `geneve`, or `disabled`, and `encryption_mode` is `wireguard`.

